# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bastion-point
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] The seaward side of the tuff crater is falling away down the coastal cliffs to 'Gentleman's Bay' far below.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] The tuff ring is made from ash and ejected material.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] The cliffs were there before the volcano erupted so the volcanic rock draped over the clay hill that once existed before sea levels rose and began eroding it away to become the steep cliffs we see today.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] Some volcanic rocks can be found on the beach below – some fragments ejected from deep in the earth, or blocks of tuff ring that were once perched on top of the cliff.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] Rangitoto Island is directly to the north, however Rangitoto is a recent eruption (600 to 550 years ago) and was not always there to shelter the cliffs from powerful wave action.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] There is an old concrete water tower built on the tuff ring formed around the edge of the crater opposite the seaward side.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] Going east, past Ladies Bay and Gentleman's Bay, we round the West Tāmaki Head into the Tāmaki Estuary.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] It is here we find an excellent example of the grey coloured 'Parnell Grit' accessible from Karaka Bay.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] 'Parnell Grit', is a brittle sedimentary rock containing fragments of scoria, andesite, and pumice.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] At low tide there is an interesting walk from Ladies Bay along the base of the cliffs to St Helier's Bay.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] The rocky shoreline overlooks the Waitemata Harbour which itself occupies a drowned valley system cut in marine sediments of Miocene Age (15–25 million years ago).
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] Generally, around Auckland these soft Miocene sediments are alternating Waitemata series sandstone and mudstone with more massive beds of sandstone sometimes with minor occurrences of limestone.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] The concretions that can be easily seen, are formed by the action of ground water with dissolved minerals (mainly calcium carbonate of which limestone is made) percolating through the layers.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] Calcium carbonate is an important component of concrete and fills in the pore spaces between grains of sediment thereby cementing the grains together and making them more durable against erosion.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] Glover Park volcano formed from a phreatomagmatic eruption leaving a basaltic monogenetic volcanic crater up to 300 m (980 ft) in maximum diameter, surrounded except to the north-east by tuff deposits that extend about 500 m (1,600 ft) to the east and south.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] The presence of overlying Rotoehu tephra on a drill ore means the volcano last erupted more than 45,000 years ago, but the age is unclear within a wide range.
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] The cliff retreat with raising sealevels of Achilles Point has meant, as already mentioned, that the tuff deposits 30 m (98 ft) up the cliffs, as they erode, fall onto the sea rock platform (see photos below).
[src:bastion-point/achilles-point] This has resulted in the discovery that a distinctive lithic clast in the tuff that contained shell fragments was strong evidence that the erupted magma traversed the eastern border of the ophiolitic Dun Mountain–Maitai terrane.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] In property law, **alienation** is the voluntary act of an owner of some property to convey or transfer the property to another.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] **Alienability** is the quality of being **alienable**, i.e., the capacity for a piece of property or a property right to be sold or otherwise transferred from one party to another.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Most property is alienable, but some may be subject to restraints on alienation.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Some objects are now regarded as ineligible for becoming property and thus termed **inalienable**, such as people and body parts.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Aboriginal title is one example of inalienability (save to the Crown) in common law jurisdictions.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] A similar concept is *non-transferability*, such as tickets.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Rights commonly described as a *licence* or permit are generally only personal and are not assignable.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] However, they are alienable in the sense that they can generally be surrendered.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] In England under the feudal system, land was generally transferred by subinfeudation, and alienation required license from the overlord.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Other early American legal commentators who praised the simple and relatively inexpensive conveyancing system in the new United States included Zaphaniah Swift, Daniel Webster and James Kent.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] English common law traditionally protected freehold landowners from unsecured creditors.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] In 1732, the Parliament of Great Britain passed legislation entitled “The Act for the More Easy Recovery of Debts in His Majesty’s Plantations and Colonies in America”, sometimes known as the Debt Recovery Act 1732 (5 Geo.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] 7), which required all land and slave property in British America to be treated as chattel for debt collection purposes.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] It thus removed the shield from creditors which had protected large, landed estates (and which continued to protect those estates in Britain).
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] However, the act was amended within a decade to allow colonial legislatures, particularly in the southern American colonies, to again protect real estate transferred in fee tail or inherited through primogeniture.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Thus, colonies which relied on enslaved labor adopted legislation which promoted the liquidity of slave property.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Although Virginia repealed laws supporting primogeniture and the fee tail in 1776, it refused to extend the Debt Recovery Act 1732 after the American Revolution, and passed further legislation which protected real estate from creditors.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Other states adopted similar legislation (some specifically protected homesteads from creditors), but the recording systems adopted throughout the new American states led to the more commodified and transferable development of American property law.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] In 1797, Parliament passed the Negroes Act 1797 (37 Geo.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] 119) which repealed the Debt Recovery Act 1732 with respect to slaves in the remaining colonies.
[src:bastion-point/alienation-property-law] Nonetheless, by 1806, abolition pamphleteers in Britain continued to criticize as cruel the act's sanction of slave auctions to satisfy a slaveowner's secured as well as unsecured debts.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] An **anti-submarine net** or **anti-submarine boom** is a boom placed across the mouth of a harbour or a strait for protection against submarines.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Net laying ships would be used to place and remove the nets.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] The US Navy used anti-submarine nets in the Pacific War to protect major US Naval Advance Bases.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Some net cutter submarines were used in the war.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Submarine nets were first used shortly after the first use of submarines in warfare, during World War I.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Because they were a reaction during the war, there was not time to study the best construction methods, or the nets' overall efficacy.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] But this was also a benefit, because the enemy did not know how effective submarine nets were either.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Testing done after the war showed that the nets used during WWI had not been effective, and yet they had acted as an effective deterrent during the war since their weaknesses were not known.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] A submarine net is very similar in principle to a boom.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] While a boom blocks a waterway for surface ships, a submarine net does the same below water.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Small ships and submarines will tend to try to slip through gaps.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Large vessels are capable of ramming through, even if they are hesitant to do so.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] The most effective way to prevent ramming is to yield slowly rather than be rigid.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] By gradually slowing a vessel to a stop the effectiveness of a barrier is greatly increased.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] The most extensive use of anti-submarine nets during WWI was the Dover Barrage, spanning the English Channel.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] It was largely effective as a deterrent.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] There were limited examples of it succeeding and failing.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] One U-boat was caught in the net, but there were also reports of submarines bypassing the net, on the surface at night, or underwater by slipping through gaps.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] From war logs there was one example of U-32 getting tangled in the Dover nets.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] The boat lay on the bottom until night, then surfaced and freed herself and continued on.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] This demonstrated that a net alone is not effective.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] It must be supported to be useful, generally by surface ships with depth charges.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] Scapa Flow is a large natural harbor in Scotland.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] It was used in WWI and WWII by the Royal Navy, and secured with submarine nets.
[src:bastion-point/anti-submarine-net] In 1918 SM UB-116 successfully bypassed the nets, though was subsequently sunk by a mine.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Te Kawau's father was Tarahawaiki and his grandfather was Tūperiri, the principal leader of Te Taoū *hapū* (sub-tribe) of Ngāti Whātua who overran the Tāmaki isthmus in the 1740s, defeating the Wai-o-Hua.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Te Kawau's mother was Mokorua, who was descended from the Wai-o-Hua.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Te Kawau was born at Ihumātao, near the Manukau Harbour.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Te Kawau is thought to have fought against the Ngāpuhi iwi in the Ngāti Whātua victory of Battle of Moremonui in 1807 or 1808.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] He then helped lead the 1,000 mile long Ngāti Whātua and Ngāti Maniapoto cannibalistic war expedition known as *Te Āmiowhenua* (encircling the land) from 1821 to 1822.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] After a major defeat to Ngāpuhi at Te Ika-a-ranga-nui in 1825, Te Kawau and his people left the Tāmaki isthmus (the future site of Auckland) for several years.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] On 20 March 1840 in the Manukau Harbour area where Ngāti Whātua farmed, Te Kawau signed *Te Tiriti o Waitangi* (the *te reo Māori* translation of the Treaty of Waitangi).
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Ngāti Whātua sought British protection from Ngāpuhi as well as a reciprocal relationship with the Crown and the Church.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Soon after signing the Treaty, Te Kawau made a *tuku* (strategic gift) of 3,500 acres (1,400 hectares) of land on the Waitematā Harbour for the new capital of Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Te Kawau was associated with the Church Mission Society (CMS) since meeting Samuel Marsden in 1820, and the two men become friends.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] During the 1840s, some time after becoming a Christian, he was baptised by Bishop George Selwyn at the chapel near Ōrākei Pā and was given the baptismal name of Āpihai, Māori for the biblical warrior Abishai.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] In the 1850s Te Kawau was an assessor involved with settling disputes between Māori in Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Known then as a peaceful man, he spoke publicly against land sales, but was unable to stop Governor George Grey's evictions and confiscations.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] In 1868 he secured the title to the last 700 acres of Ngāti Whātua land in Ōrākei for his iwi.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] Te Kawau was the uncle of Paora Tūhaere, who succeeded him as a leader of Ngāti Whātua.
[src:bastion-point/apihai-te-kawau] In 2018 Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei and the Ports of Auckland created a memorial to Te Kawau for his gifting of land to Governor Hobson and commemorating his contributions to Auckland, while marking the place where the city was founded on 18 September 1840.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] The councillors and the mayor of Auckland City were elected every three years.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] Amongst its other functions, the city council administered more than 700 parks and reserves throughout the city (2008 data).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] Auckland City, as part of its landscaping programmes, had planted more than 103,000 trees since 2002, with about 16,000 new trees in 2008, a rate that was estimated at four times the trimming and removal rate of public and private trees.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] In the financial year ending June 2007, Auckland City Council had operating revenue of NZ$552 million, of which 68% came from Council rates, which were NZ$859 per ratepayer on average.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] It expended NZ$343 million on capital projects, of which 45% went to 'transport' expenses, 19% to 'property and asset management' and 17% to 'open spaces, parks and streetscapes', while 10% were spent on 'stormwater and waste management'.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] Another 7% were spent on 'arts and culture' and 2% on 'zoo, recreational facilities and community development'.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] The operating surplus was NZ$40.3 million.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] In 2002 then mayor John Banks announced plans to sell 1570 of its 1700 pensioner flats.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] A coalition called Council Housing Action Group (CHAG) fought the privatisation.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] Initially Banks sought to sell the flats on the private market, and the coalition protests included disrupting private auctions.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] While the coalition was unable to prevent the sell-off, they achieved a substantial "compromise" where the flats were not sold off privately but instead sold to Housing New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] All 1542 pensioner flats and 129 residential houses owned by Auckland City Council were sold to Housing NZ for $83million in 2002-3.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] The "book value" for all was $132million at the time of sale.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] In 2003, a contract award decision concerning waste collection and disposal services was challenged by an unsuccessful tenderer, Onyx Environnement (part of the international Veolia Group).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] The city's invitation to tender, first launched in 2000, sought proposals for waste collection in the eastern and western parts of the city, with the potential for two separate contracts to be awarded.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] On separate analysis, Onyx's tenders for each division offered the best value, but the other tenderers offered a discount if their bids were amalgamated and a cross-city contract was awarded.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] Onyx had not included this provision in their submission, which meant that once this proposal was considered, they were no longer the lowest-cost bidder.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] They challenged the contract award decision but the High Court upheld the Council's right to consider such a "non-compliant" proposal.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] Justice Mark O'Regan held that the Council's tendering rules allowed it such discretion and noted that the Council had sought external advice before going ahead with its decision.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-city-council] The Council's lawyers welcomed the ruling as significant for all New Zealand local authorities undertaking public procurement activities.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The governing body consists of a mayor and 20 councillors, elected from 13 wards.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] There are also 151 members of 21 local boards who make decisions on matters local to their communities.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The council was established by a number of Acts of Parliament, and an Auckland Transition Agency, also created by the central government.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Both the means by which the council was established and its structure came under repeated criticism from a broad spectrum during the establishment period.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The Auckland Regional Council was formed in 1989, replacing the Auckland Regional Authority.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] One of the mainstays of its work was expanding the parks network, and it brought into the Auckland Council 26 regional parks with more than 40,000 hectares, including many restored natural habitats and sanctuaries developed in co-operation with the Department of Conservation and volunteers.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Until 2010, the Auckland Region had seven "City/District" authorities, plus one "Regional" authority.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] In 2007, the government set up a Royal Commission on Auckland Governance to report on what restructuring should be done.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] On 23 March 2023, the Auckland Council voted by a margin of ten to ten to leave Local Government New Zealand (LGNZ), the national representative body for local councils in New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Mayor Brown used his casting vote to break the deadlock during the Council's vote.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Brown said that members of the body got drunk regularly during conference meetings and that the Auckland Council could negotiate with the New Zealand Government independently.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Brown also said that exiting the LGNZ would save the Auckland Council NZ$640,000 a year, helping to reduce its debt.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The Auckland Council's decision to leave LGNZ was criticised as detrimental to Auckland ratepayers and cooperation with other local councils by fellow councillors Richard Hills, Andy Baker, Julie Fairey, and LGNZ President Stuart Crosby.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The governing body of the Auckland Council consists of the mayor and councillors.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Decision-making for the governing body's areas of oversight is done by committees, a few of which consist of the whole governing body, and most of which consist of a chairperson appointed by the mayor and a subset of the governing body members.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The mayor of Auckland is the directly elected chair of the governing body of Auckland Council.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Doug McKay was announced as the inaugural chief executive officer of the council, being selected ahead of 27 other.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] He had no direct experience in local government, but had strong ties to Auckland; he had 30 years of experience as a corporate executive.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] He was to receive a salary of $675,000 and an incentive bonus of $67,500.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Stephen Town became chief executive on 15 January 2014.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] In early February 2020, Town announced he would not see out his term until December 2020, moving to the New Zealand Institute of Skills & Technology in early July.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Auckland Council has several council-controlled organisations (CCOs).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] These include any organisation of which the Council appoints at least 50% of its board members.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] CCOs that are responsible for a significant service or activity, or those who manage assets worth more than $10 million are described as substantive.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] In mid-June 2026, the populist New Zealand First party announced it would campaign during the 2026 New Zealand general election on disestablishing the Independent Māori Statutory Board as part of its campaign against co-governance.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The council was set up by three pieces of legislation, the Local Government (Tamaki Makaurau Reorganisation) Act 2009, the Local Government (Auckland Council) Act 2009 and the Local Government (Auckland Transitional Provisions) Act 2010.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The Council owns approximately $34 billion of assets (2010), including over 100,000 hectares of open space, parks and reserves, as well as the large transport assets administered by the Auckland Transport CCO (see that article for more detail).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The council owns and manages 28 regional parks around the region.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Most of the parks were inherited from Auckland Regional Council.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Auckland Council rates combine the rates of the various amalgamated local councils and the Auckland Regional Council rates.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] For the 2011–2012 year, ratepayers are being charged the same rate as before the amalgamation, plus a 3.94% increase, with Council noting that they had achieved a much lower rates increase than originally foreseen.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Rates made up 53% of the Council's income in 2011, with the remainder being "grants, subsidies, development and financial contributions, user charges and fees".
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] As of 2011, 24% of the Council's money was spent on "Art services and galleries, events, museums, parks, recreation facilities and the zoo", while 22% was spent on "transport management".
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Further big elements were "Planning and regulation" at 14.5% and "Community services, libraries, emergency management and cemeteries" at 11.5%.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] As of 2016, 38% of rates were spent on "transport", 27% on "parks, community and lifestyle", 16% on "environmental management and regulation", 8% on "Auckland development", 6% on "Economic and cultural development" and 5% on "governance and support".
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The initial Council elections in October 2010 returned a mostly centre-left council, with Len Brown as mayor.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Brown was re-elected in October 2013, again with a largely supportive council.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] The 2016 mayoral election was won by Labour MP Phil Goff, who had a landslide victory over his nearest rivals, Victoria Crone and future Green Party MP Chlöe Swarbrick.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] Goff won re-election in the 2019 mayoral election and chose not to run in the 2022 mayoral election, which was won by Wayne Brown.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-council] In the 2025 mayoral election, Brown was re-elected with an absolute majority.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The city lies between the Hauraki Gulf to the east, the Hunua Ranges to the south-east, the Manukau Harbour to the south-west, and the Waitākere Ranges and smaller ranges to the west and north-west.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The surrounding hills are covered in rainforest and the landscape is dotted with 53 volcanic centres that make up the Auckland Volcanic Field.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The central part of the urban area occupies a narrow isthmus between the Manukau Harbour on the Tasman Sea and the Waitematā Harbour on the Pacific Ocean.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland is one of the few cities in the world to have a harbour on each of two separate major bodies of water.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland isthmus was first settled c.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] 1350 and was valued for its rich and fertile land.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Māori population in the area is estimated to have peaked at 20,000 before the arrival of Europeans.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] After a British colony was established in New Zealand in 1840, William Hobson, then Lieutenant-Governor of New Zealand, chose Auckland as its new capital.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei made a strategic gift of land to Hobson for the new capital.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] During the New Zealand wars many fencibles and soldiers were stationed in and around Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] It has been the nation's largest city throughout most of its history.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Today, Auckland's central business district is New Zealand's leading economic hub.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] While Europeans continue to make up the plurality of Auckland's population, the city became multicultural and cosmopolitan in the late 20th century, with Asians accounting for 34.9% of the city's population in 2023.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In 2016 Auckland had the fourth largest foreign-born population in the world, with 39% of its residents born overseas.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] With its sizeable population of Pasifika New Zealanders, the city is also home to the largest ethnic Polynesian population in the world.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The University of Auckland, founded in 1883, is the largest university in New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The city's significant tourist attractions include national historic sites, festivals, performing arts, sports activities and a variety of cultural institutions, such as the Auckland War Memorial Museum, the Museum of Transport and Technology, and the Auckland Art Gallery.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Its architectural landmarks include the Harbour Bridge, the Town Hall, the Ferry Building and the Sky Tower, which is the second-tallest building in the Southern Hemisphere after Thamrin Nine.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The city is served by Auckland Airport, which handled 18.5 million passengers in 2024.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland is one of the world's most liveable cities, ranking fifth in the 2024 Mercer Quality of Living Survey and ninth in the 2024 Global Liveability Ranking by *The Economist*.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Māori-language name for Auckland is **Tāmaki Makaurau**, meaning "Tāmaki desired by many", in reference to the desirability of its natural resources and geography.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] There are various theories of the origin of the name "Tāmaki", which is also used to refer to an eastern suburb of Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] It is regarded by some to be the isthmus between the two harbours of the area, which is variously said to be named after a son of Maruiwi from Taranaki, a line of chiefs from the southern Taranaki, or a female leader of Ngāti Te Ata.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Other versions of the name include *Tāmakinui* (great Tāmaki) or *Tāmaki-herehere-ngā-waka* (Tāmaki that binds many canoes).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] William Hobson named the area after George Eden, Earl of Auckland, British First Lord of the Admiralty.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Earldom of Auckland was named after West Auckland, a village in County Durham, Northern England.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The name "Auckland" in West Auckland is thought to originate from the Cumbric word "*Alclud*", which was the Kingdom of Strathclyde's alternative name meaning "cliff on the Clyde".
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] It is thought 'Clyde' may be the river Gaunless' old name.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland is popularly nicknamed the "City of Sails" or the "Queen City".
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland isthmus was settled by Māori around 1350, and was valued for its rich and fertile land.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Many pā (fortified villages) were built, mainly on the volcanic peaks.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] By the early 1700s, Te Waiohua, a confederation of tribes such as Ngā Oho, Ngā Riki and Ngā Iwi, was the main tribal group on the Auckland isthmus, with major pā at Maungakiekie / One Tree Hill, Māngere Mountain and Maungataketake.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The confederation came to an end around 1741 when paramount chief Kiwi Tāmaki was killed in battle by Te Waha-akiaki, a chief of the Ngāti Whātua hapū Te Taoū.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] From the 1740s, Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei were the main tribe on the Auckland isthmus.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Māori population in the area is estimated to have been about 20,000 before the arrival of Europeans.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The introduction of firearms at the end of the eighteenth century, which began in Northland, upset the balance of power and led to devastating intertribal warfare beginning in 1807, causing iwi who lacked the new weapons to seek refuge in areas less exposed to coastal raids.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] As a result, the region had relatively low numbers of Māori when settlement by European New Zealanders began.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] On 20 March 1840 in the Manukau Harbour area where Ngāti Whātua farmed, paramount chief Apihai Te Kawau signed the Treaty of Waitangi.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Soon after signing the treaty, Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei made a strategic gift of 3,500 acres (1,400 ha) of land on the Waitematā Harbour to the new Governor of New Zealand, William Hobson, for the new capital, which Hobson named for George Eden, Earl of Auckland, then Viceroy of India.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland was founded on 18 September 1840 and was officially declared New Zealand's capital in 1841, and the transfer of the administration from Russell (now Old Russell) in the Bay of Islands was completed in 1842.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] However, even in 1840 Port Nicholson (later renamed Wellington) was seen as a better choice for an administrative capital because of its proximity to the South Island, and Wellington became the capital in 1865.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] After losing its status as capital, Auckland remained the principal city of the Auckland Province until the provincial system was abolished in 1876.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In response to the ongoing rebellion by Hōne Heke in the mid-1840s, the government encouraged retired but fit British soldiers and their families to migrate to Auckland to form a defence line around the port settlement as garrison soldiers.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] By the time the first Fencibles arrived in 1848, the Northern War had concluded.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Outlying defensive towns were then constructed to the south, stretching in a line from the port village of Onehunga in the west to Howick in the east.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Each of the four settlements had about 800 settlers.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In the early 1860s, Auckland became a base against the Māori King Movement, and the 12,000 Imperial soldiers stationed there gave a strong boost to local commerce.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] This, and continued road building towards the south into the Waikato region, enabled Pākehā (European New Zealanders) influence to spread from Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The growth occurred similarly to other mercantile-dominated cities, mainly around the port and with problems of overcrowding and pollution.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland's population of ex-soldiers was far greater than that of other settlements: about 50 per cent of the population was Irish, which contrasted heavily with the majority English settlers in Wellington, Christchurch or New Plymouth.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The majority of settlers in the early period were assisted by receiving cheap passage to New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Trams and railway lines shaped Auckland's rapid expansion in the early first half of the 20th century.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] However, after the Second World War, the city's transport system and urban form became increasingly dominated by the motor vehicle.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Arterial roads and motorways became both defining and geographically dividing features of the urban landscape.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] They also allowed further massive expansion that resulted in the growth of suburban areas such as the North Shore (especially after the construction of the Auckland Harbour Bridge in the late 1950s), and Manukau City in the south.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Economic deregulation in the mid-1980s led to very dramatic changes to Auckland's economy, and many companies relocated their head offices from Wellington to Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The region was now the nerve centre of the entire national economy.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland also benefited from a surge in tourism, which brought 75 per cent of New Zealand's international visitors through its airport.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland's port handled 31 per cent of the country's container trade in 2015.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The face of urban Auckland changed when the government's immigration policy began allowing immigrants from Asia in 1986.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] This has led to Auckland becoming a multicultural city, with people of all ethnic backgrounds.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] According to the 1961 census data, Māori and Pacific Islanders made up five per cent of Auckland's population; Asians less than one per cent.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The city became home to the world's largest Polynesian population by the 1990s.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] By 2006, the Asian population had reached 18.0 per cent in Auckland, and 36.2 per cent in the central city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] New arrivals from Hong Kong, Taiwan and Korea gave a distinctive character to the areas where they clustered, while a range of other immigrants introduced mosques, Hindu temples, Buddhist temples, halal and kosher butchers and ethnic restaurants to the suburbs.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The boundaries of Auckland are imprecisely defined.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland urban area, as it is defined by Statistics New Zealand under the *Statistical Standard for Geographic Areas 2018* (SSGA18), spans 607.07 square kilometres (234.39 sq mi) and extends to Long Bay in the north, Swanson in the north-west, and Runciman in the south.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland forms New Zealand's largest urban area.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland urban area lies within the Auckland Region, an administrative region that takes its name from the city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The region encompasses the city centre, as well as suburbs, surrounding towns, nearshore islands, and rural areas north and south of the urban area.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland central business district is the most built-up area of the region.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The CBD covers 433 hectares (1,070 acres) in a triangular area, and is bounded by the Auckland waterfront on the Waitematā Harbour and the inner-city suburbs of Ponsonby, Newton and Parnell.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland cityscape viewed from Maungawhau / Mount Eden.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The central areas of the city are located on the Auckland isthmus, less than two kilometres wide at its narrowest point, between Māngere Inlet and the Tāmaki River.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] There are two harbours surrounding this isthmus: Waitematā Harbour to the north, which extends east to the Hauraki Gulf and thence to the Pacific Ocean, and Manukau Harbour to the south, which opens west to the Tasman Sea.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Bridges span parts of both harbours, notably the Auckland Harbour Bridge crossing the Waitematā Harbour west of the central business district.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Māngere Bridge and the Upper Harbour Bridge span the upper reaches of the Manukau and Waitematā Harbours, respectively.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In earlier times, portages crossed the narrowest sections of the isthmus.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Several islands of the Hauraki Gulf are administered as part of the Auckland Region, though they are not part of the Auckland urban area.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Parts of Waiheke Island effectively function as Auckland suburbs, while various smaller islands near Auckland are mostly zoned 'recreational open space' or are nature sanctuaries.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification, Auckland has an oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification *Cfb*).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] However, under the Trewartha climate classification and according to the National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research (NIWA), the city's climate is classified as humid subtropical climate with warm summers and mild winters (Trewartha climate classification *Cfbl*).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] It is the warmest main centre of New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Snowfall is extremely rare: the most significant fall since the start of the 20th century was on 27 July 1939, when snow fell just before dawn and five centimetres (2 in) of snow reportedly lay on Mount Eden.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Snowflakes were also seen on 28 July 1930 and 15 August 2011.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Frosts in Auckland are infrequent and often localised.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Henderson Riverpark receives an annual average of 27.4 ground frosts per year, while Auckland Airport receives an annual average of 8.7 ground frosts per year.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Average sea temperature around Auckland varies throughout the year.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The water temperature is warmest in February when it averages 21 °C (70 °F), while in August, the water temperature is at its coolest, averaging 14 °C (57 °F).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Prevailing winds in Auckland are predominantly from the southwest.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The mean annual wind speed for Auckland Airport is 18 kilometres per hour (11 mph).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] During the summer months there is often a sea breeze in Auckland which starts in the morning and dies down again in the evening.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The early morning calm on the isthmus during settled weather, before the sea breeze rises, was described as early as 1853: "In all seasons, the beauty of the day is in the early morning.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] At that time, generally, a solemn stillness holds, and a perfect calm prevails...".
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Fog is a common occurrence for Auckland, especially in autumn and winter.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Whenuapai Airport experiences an average of 44 fog days per year.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland occasionally suffers from air pollution due to fine particle emissions.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] There are also occasional breaches of guideline levels of carbon monoxide.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] While maritime winds normally disperse the pollution relatively quickly it can sometimes become visible as smog, especially on calm winter days.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The record low temperature is −5.7 °C (21.7 °F) recorded at Riverhead Forest in June 1936, while the maximum recorded temperature is 34.0 °C (93.2 °F) on 12 February 2009.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The record lowest daily maximum is 8.0 °C (46.4 °F) recorded on both 13 June 1976 and 16 August 2011.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The record highest daily minimum is 23.6 °C (74.5 °F) on 12 February 2022.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The record highest dew point is 25.0 °C (77.0 °F) recorded on 10 March 1972.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The most humid month on record was January 2018 with an average dew point of 18.0 °C (64.4 °F).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The warmest month on record was February 1990 with an average mean temperature of 22.1 °C (71.8 °F).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The city of Auckland straddles the Auckland Volcanic Field, an area which in the past, produced at least 53 small volcanic centres over the last ~193,000 years, represented by a range of surface features including maars (explosion craters), tuff rings, scoria cones, and lava flows.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] It is fed entirely by basaltic magma sourced from the mantle at a depth of 70–90 km below the city, and is unrelated to the explosive, subduction-driven volcanism of the Taupō Volcanic Zone in the Central North Island region of Aotearoa, New Zealand, ~250 km away.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland Volcanic Field is considered to be a monogenetic volcanic field, with each volcano erupting only a single time, usually over a timeframe of weeks to years before cessation of activity.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Future eruptive activity remains a threat to the city, and will likely occur at a new, unknown location within the field.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The most recent activity occurred approximately 1450 AD at the Rangitoto Volcano.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] This event was witnessed by Māori occupants of the area, making it the only eruption within the Auckland Volcanic Field thus far to have been observed by humans.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland Volcanic Field has contributed greatly to the growth and prosperity of the Auckland Region since the area was settled by humans.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Initially, the maunga (scoria cones) were occupied and established as pā (fortified settlements) by Māori due to the strategic advantage their elevation provided in controlling resources and key portages between the Waitematā and Manukau harbours.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The rich volcanic soils found in these areas also proved ideal for the cultivation of crops, such as kūmara.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Following European arrival, many of the maunga were transformed into quarries to supply the growing city with aggregate and building materials, and as a result were severely damaged or entirely destroyed.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] A number of the smaller maar craters and tuff rings were also removed during earthworks.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Most of the remaining volcanic centres are now preserved within recreational reserves administered by Auckland Council, the Department of Conservation, and the Tūpuna Maunga o Tāmaki Makaurau Authority.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland urban area, as defined by Statistics New Zealand, covers 605.67 km2 (233.85 sq mi).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The urban area has an estimated population of 1,547,200 as of June 2025, 29.1 percent of New Zealand's population.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The city has a population larger than the entire South Island (1,256,700).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The urban area had a population of 1,402,275 in the 2023 New Zealand census, an increase of 56,442 people (4.2%) since the 2018 census, and an increase of 178,734 people (14.6%) since the 2013 census.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The median age was 35.1 years (compared with 38.1 years nationally).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Of those at least 15 years old, 290,814 (25.7%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, 464,022 (41.0%) had a post-high school certificate or diploma, and 298,851 (26.4%) people exclusively held high school qualifications.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The median income was $44,600, compared with $41,500 nationally.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Many ethnic groups, since the late 20th century, have had an increasing presence in Auckland, making it by far the country's most cosmopolitan city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Historically, Auckland's population has been of majority European origin, though the proportion of those of Asian or other non-European origins has increased in recent decades due to the removal of restrictions directly or indirectly based on race.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Europeans continue to make up the plurality of the city's population, but no longer constitute a majority after decreasing in proportion from 54.6% to 48.1% between the 2013 and 2018 censuses.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Asians now form the second-largest ethnic group, making up nearly one-third of the population.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland is home to the largest ethnic Polynesian population of any city in the world, with a sizeable population of Pacific Islanders (Pasifika) and indigenous Māori people.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] English was spoken by 91.5%, Māori language by 2.7%, Samoan by 5.3% and other languages by 32.0%.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] No language could be spoken by 2.4% (e.g. too young to talk).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] New Zealand Sign Language was known by 0.4%.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The percentage of people born overseas was 44.9%, compared with 28.8% nationally.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] At the 2023 census the Pasifika population formed the majority in the Māngere-Ōtāhuhu local board area and the plurality in the Ōtara-Papatoetoe and Manurewa local board areas.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Asian population formed the majority in the Howick and Puketāpapa local board areas and the plurality in the Whau local board area.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Europeans formed the plurality in the Henderson-Massey, Maungakiekie-Tāmaki and Papakura local board areas, and formed the majority in the remaining 11 local board areas.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Māori did not form a majority or plurality in any local board area but are in the highest concentrations in the Manurewa and Papakura local board areas.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Immigration to New Zealand is heavily concentrated towards Auckland (partly for job market reasons).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] This strong focus on Auckland has led the immigration services to award extra points towards immigration visa requirements for people intending to move to other parts of New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Immigration from overseas into Auckland is partially offset by the net emigration of people from Auckland to other regions of New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In 2021 and 2022, Auckland recorded its only decreases in population, primarily due to the COVID-19 pandemic and the associated lack of international migration.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] At the 2018 Census, in the local board areas of Upper Harbour, Waitematā, Puketāpapa and Howick, overseas-born residents outnumbered those born in New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] A study from 2016 showed Auckland has the fourth largest foreign-born population in the world, only behind Dubai, Toronto and Brussels, with 39% of its residents born overseas.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Religious affiliations in the 2023 census were 35.7% Christian, 6.1% Hindu, 3.3% Islam, 0.9% Māori religious beliefs, 2.1% Buddhist, 0.3% New Age, 0.2% Jewish, and 2.8% other religions.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] People who answered that they had no religion were 42.7%, and 6.0% of people did not answer the census question.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In 2007, immigration from Asia has added to the religious diversity of the city, increasing the number of people affiliating with Buddhism, Hinduism, Islam and Sikhism, although there are no figures on religious attendance.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] There is also a small, long-established Jewish community.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland is experiencing substantial population growth via immigration (two-thirds of growth) and natural population increases (one-third), and is set to grow to an estimated 1.9 million inhabitants by 2031 in a medium-variant scenario.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] This substantial increase in population will have a huge impact on transport, housing and other infrastructure that are, particularly in the case of housing, that are considered to be under pressure already.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The high-variant scenario shows the region's population growing to over two million by 2031.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In July 2016, Auckland Council released, as the outcome of a three-year study and public hearings, its Unitary Plan for Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The plan aims to free up to 30 percent more land for housing and allows for greater intensification of the existing urban area, creating 422,000 new dwellings in the next 30 years.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In 1851, Auckland was constituted as an independent borough, the first in the country.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The borough was 58,000 acres (23,000 ha) in size and went as far west as the Whau River and as far east as Howick.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The large boundary included 4,000 Europeans in the urban areas; 2,500 in the Fencible settlements; and 1,500 in the rural parts.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] An inability to collect rates and a divide between urban and rural interests led to the borough becoming defunct in 1852.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In 1854, the Auckland Provincial Council established Auckland City under the Auckland City Council Act.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] This city had boundaries equivalent to the City of Auckland electorate.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The legality of this city was challenged and it was later dissolved in March 1855 before finally being repealed by an act in April 1856.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] An Auckland Harbour Board was also established and repealed during the same period.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In 1863, the Town of Auckland was incorporated within the same boundaries of the East Town, Middle Town, and West Town wards of the borough.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] On 24 April 1871, Auckland became a city under *The Municipal Corporations Act, 1867*.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland Council is the local authority with jurisdiction over the city of Auckland, along with surrounding rural areas, parkland, and the islands of the Hauraki Gulf.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] From 1989 to 2010, Auckland was governed by several city and district councils, with regional oversight by Auckland Regional Council.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] A Royal Commission on Auckland Governance was set up in 2007; in 2009, it recommended a unified local governance structure for Auckland by amalgamating the councils.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The government subsequently announced that a "super city" would be set up with a single mayor by the time of New Zealand's local body elections in 2010.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In October 2010, Manukau City mayor Len Brown was elected mayor of the amalgamated Auckland Council.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] He was re-elected for a second term in October 2013.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Brown did not stand for re-election in the 2016 mayoral election, and was succeeded by successful candidate Phil Goff in October 2016.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Twenty councillors make up the remainder of the Auckland Council governing body, elected from thirteen electoral wards.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Between 1842 and 1865, Auckland was the capital city of New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Parliament met in what is now Old Government House on the University of Auckland's City campus.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The capital was moved to the more centrally located Wellington in 1865.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland, due to its large population, is covered by 23 general electorates and three Māori electorates, each returning one member to the New Zealand House of Representatives.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The National Party holds 14 general electorates, the Labour Party six, ACT two and the Greens one.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Two of the three Māori electorates are held by Te Pāti Māori; the remaining Māori electorate is held by an independent.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In 1891, the three main items exported from Auckland's port were: kauri gum, gold, and wool.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] These exports were collectively worth almost a million pounds.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland is the major economic and financial centre of New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] It has an advanced market economy with strengths in finance, commerce, and tourism.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Most major international corporations have an Auckland office; the most expensive office space is around lower Queen Street and the Viaduct Basin in the Auckland CBD, where many financial and business services are located, which constitute a large percentage of the CBD economy.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The largest commercial and industrial areas of the Auckland Region are Auckland CBD and the western parts of Manukau, mostly bordering the Manukau Harbour and the Tāmaki River estuary.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The GDP of Auckland in 2025 was estimated at $167 billion NZD, which saw a 2.1% increase from 2023.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The per-capita GDP of Auckland was estimated at $91,960 at the end of 2025, the second-highest in the country after the Wellington region, and above the national average of $87,400.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland has a diversity of architectural styles, resulting from its early beginnings as a settlement, the Victorian period, the 20th century and through to the contemporary era of the 21st century.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Legislation is in effect to protect the remaining heritage, with the key piece being the Resource Management Act of 1991.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Prepared under this legislation is the Auckland Unitary Plan, which indicates how land can be used or developed.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Prominent historic buildings in Auckland include the Dilworth Building, the Auckland Ferry Terminal, Guardian Trust Building, Old Customs House, Landmark House, the Auckland Town Hall and the Britomart Transport Centre – many of these are located on Queen Street, the main street.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Housing varies considerably, between suburbs that have state-owned housing in lower income neighbourhoods, to larger waterfront homes, especially in areas close to the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Historically, the most common residence of Aucklanders was a standalone dwelling on a 'quarter acre' (1,000 m2).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] However, subdividing such properties with 'infill housing' has long been the norm.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland's housing stock has become more diverse in recent decades, with many more apartments being built since the 1970s, particularly since the 1990s in the CBD.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Nevertheless, the majority of Aucklanders live in single dwelling housing and are expected to continue to do so, even with most of future urban growth being through intensification.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland has been described as having "the most extensive range of timbered housing with its classical details and mouldings in the world", many of them built in the Victorian and Edwardian eras.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In some areas, the Victorian villas have been torn down to make way for redevelopment.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The demolition of the older houses is being combated through increased heritage protection for older parts of the city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland's housing is amongst the least affordable in the world, based on comparing average house prices with average household income levels and house prices have grown well above the rate of inflation in recent decades.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] There is significant public debate around why Auckland's housing is so expensive, often referring to a lack of land supply, the easy availability of credit for residential investment and Auckland's high level of liveability.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In the lead-up to 2010, a housing crisis began in Auckland, with the market not being able to sustain the demand for affordable homes.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Housing Accords and Special Housing Areas Act 2013 mandated that a minimum of 10 percent of new builds in certain housing areas be subsidised to make them affordable for buyers who had incomes on par with the national average.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] In a new subdivision at Hobsonville Point, 20 percent of new homes were reduced to below $550,000.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Some of the demand for new housing at this time was attributed to the 43,000 people who moved into Auckland between June 2014 and June 2015.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Research has found that Auckland is set to become even more densely populated in future which could ease the burden by creating higher density housing in the city centre.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] From around November 2021 to May 2022, house prices dropped 11.68%.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] It has continued to fall since due to inflation, bank interest rates, and a variety of other factors.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Positive aspects of Auckland life are its mild climate, plentiful employment and educational opportunities, as well as numerous leisure facilities.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Meanwhile, traffic problems, the lack of good public transport, and increasing housing costs have been cited by many Aucklanders as among the strongest negative factors of living there, together with crime that has been rising in recent years.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Nonetheless, Auckland ranked third in a survey of the quality of life of 215 major cities of the world (2015 data).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] One of Auckland's nicknames, the "City of Sails", is derived from the popularity of sailing in the region.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] 135,000 yachts and launches are registered in Auckland, and around 60,500 of the country's 149,900 registered yachtsmen are from Auckland, with about one in three Auckland households owning a boat.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Viaduct Basin, on the western edge of the CBD, hosted three America's Cup challenges (2000 Cup, 2003 Cup and 2021 Cup).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Waitematā Harbour is home to several notable yacht clubs and marinas, including the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron and Westhaven Marina, the largest of the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Waitematā Harbour has several swimming beaches, including Mission Bay and Kohimarama on the south side of the harbour, and Stanley Bay on the north side.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The west coast has popular surf beaches such as Piha, Muriwai and Te Henga (Bethells Beach).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Whangaparāoa Peninsula, Orewa, Ōmaha and Pākiri, to the north of the main urban area, are also nearby.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Many Auckland beaches are patrolled by surf lifesaving clubs, such as Piha Surf Life Saving Club the home of Piha Rescue.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] All surf lifesaving clubs are part of the Surf Life Saving Northern Region.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Queen Street, Britomart, Ponsonby Road, Karangahape Road, Newmarket and Parnell are major retail areas.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Major markets include those held in Ōtara and Avondale on weekend mornings.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] A number of shopping centres are located in the middle- and outer-suburbs, with Westfield Newmarket, Sylvia Park, Botany Town Centre and Westfield Albany being the largest.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] A number of arts events are held in Auckland, including the Auckland Festival, the Auckland Triennial, the New Zealand International Comedy Festival, and the New Zealand International Film Festival.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland Philharmonia is the city and region's resident full-time symphony orchestra, performing its own series of concerts and accompanying opera and ballet.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Events celebrating the city's cultural diversity include the Pasifika Festival, the Auckland Secondary Schools Māori & Pacific Islands Cultural Festival (more commonly known as Polyfest), and the Auckland Lantern Festival, all of which are the largest of their kind in New Zealand.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Additionally, Auckland regularly hosts the New Zealand Symphony Orchestra and Royal New Zealand Ballet.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland is part of the UNESCO Creative Cities Network in the category of music.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Important institutions include the Auckland Art Gallery, Auckland War Memorial Museum, New Zealand Maritime Museum, National Museum of the Royal New Zealand Navy, and the Museum of Transport and Technology.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland Art Gallery is the largest stand-alone gallery in New Zealand with a collection of over 17,000 artworks, including prominent New Zealand and Pacific Island artists, as well as international painting, sculpture and print collections ranging in date from 1376 to the present day.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Other important art galleries include Mangere Arts Centre, Tautai Pacific Arts Trust, Te Tuhi, Te Uru Waitākere Contemporary Gallery, Gow Langsford Gallery, Michael Lett Gallery, Starkwhite, and Bergman Gallery.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Auckland Domain is one of the largest parks in the city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Smaller parks close to the city centre are Albert Park, Myers Park, Western Park and Victoria Park.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] While most volcanic cones in the Auckland volcanic field have been affected by quarrying, many of the remaining cones are now within parks, and retain a more natural character than the surrounding city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Prehistoric earthworks and historic fortifications are in several of these parks, including Maungawhau / Mount Eden, North Head and Maungakiekie / One Tree Hill.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Other parks around the city are in Western Springs Reserve, which has a large park bordering the MOTAT museum and the Auckland Zoo.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Auckland Botanic Gardens are further south, in Manurewa.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] Ferries provide transport to parks and nature reserves at Devonport, Waiheke Island, Rangitoto Island and Tiritiri Matangi.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p01] The Waitākere Ranges Regional Park to the west of Auckland has relatively unspoiled bush territory, as do the Hunua Ranges to the south.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] During the 19th century the main forms of transport to and from Auckland were ferries and trains, with horses being used for shorter distances and trips within the city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] From 1902 electric trams provided transport for the central isthmus and resulted in residential expansion in the area.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Following the First World War car ownership started to increase and concrete and bitumen roads were built to accommodate this.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The State Highway network connects the different parts of Auckland, with State Highway 1 the major north–south thoroughfare through the city (including both the Northern and Southern Motorways) and the main connection to the adjoining regions of Northland and Waikato.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The Northern Busway runs alongside part of the Northern Motorway on the North Shore.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Other state highways within Auckland include State Highway 16 (the Northwest Motorway), State Highway 18 (the Upper Harbour Motorway) and State Highway 20 (the Southwest Motorway).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] State Highway 22 is a non-motorway rural arterial connecting Pukekohe to the Southern Motorway at Drury.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The Auckland Harbour Bridge, opened in 1959, is the main connection between the North Shore and the rest of Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The bridge provides eight lanes of vehicle traffic and has a moveable median barrier for lane flexibility, but does not provide access for rail, pedestrians or cyclists.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The Central Motorway Junction, also called 'Spaghetti Junction' for its complexity, is the intersection between the two major motorways of Auckland (State Highway 1 and State Highway 16).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Two of the longest arterial roads within the Auckland Region are Great North Road and Great South Road – the main connections in those directions before the construction of the State Highway network.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Numerous arterial roads also provide regional and sub-regional connectivity, with many of these roads (especially on the isthmus) previously used to operate Auckland's former tram network.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland has four railway lines (Western, Onehunga, Eastern and Southern).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] These lines serve the western, southern and eastern parts of Auckland from the Waitematā railway station in downtown Auckland, the terminal station for all lines, where connections are also available to ferry and bus services.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Work began in late 2015 to provide more route flexibility and connect Britomart, now named Waitematā, more directly to the western suburbs on the Western Line via an underground rail tunnel known as the City Rail Link project.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] A plan for a light rail network was cancelled in 2024.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland Airport, New Zealand's largest and busiest, is in the southern suburb of Māngere on the shores of the Manukau Harbour.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] It services both domestic and international flights.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] There are also several small regional airports.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland's ports are the second largest in the country, behind the Port of Tauranga, and a large part of both inbound and outbound New Zealand commerce travels through them, mostly via the facilities northeast of Auckland CBD.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Freight usually arrives at or is distributed from the port via road, though the port facilities also have rail access.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland is a major cruise ship stopover point, with the ships usually tying up at Princes Wharf.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland CBD is connected to the coastal suburbs, to the North Shore and to outlying islands by ferry.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Private vehicles are the main form of transportation within Auckland, with around seven percent of journeys in the Auckland Region undertaken by bus in 2006, and two percent undertaken by train and ferry.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] For trips to the city centre at peak times, the use of public transport is much higher, with more than half of trips undertaken by bus, train or ferry.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] In 2010, Auckland ranked quite low in its use of public transport, having only 46 public transport trips per capita per year, while Wellington has almost twice this number at 91, and Sydney has 114 trips.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] This strong dependence on roads results in substantial traffic congestion during peak times.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] This car reliance means 56% of the city's energy usage goes towards transportation, and CO2 emissions will increase by 20% in the next 10 years.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Bus services in Auckland consist mostly of radial and cross-town routes.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Late-night services (i.e. past midnight) are limited, even on weekends.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] A major overhaul of Auckland's bus services was implemented during 2016–18, significantly expanding the reach of frequent bus services: those that operate at least every 15 minutes during the day and early evening, every day of the week.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland is connected with other cities through bus services operated by InterCity.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Rail services operate along four lines between the CBD and the west, south and south-east of Auckland, with longer-distance trains operating to Wellington only a few times each week.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Following the opening of Waitematā railway station in 2003, major investment in Auckland's rail network occurred, involving station upgrades, rolling stock refurbishment and infrastructure improvements.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The rail upgrade has included electrification of Auckland's rail network, with electric trains constructed by Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles commencing service in April 2014.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] A number of proposed projects to further extend Auckland's rail network were included in the 2012 Auckland Plan, including the City Rail Link, the Auckland Airport Line, the Avondale-Southdown Line and rail to the North Shore.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Research at Griffith University has indicated that from the 1950s to the 1980s, Auckland engaged in some of the most pro-automobile transport policies anywhere in the world.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Vector owns and operates the majority of the distribution network in urban Auckland, with Counties Energy owning and operating the network south of central Papakura.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The city is supplied from Transpower's national grid from thirteen substations across the city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] There are no major electricity generation stations located within the city or north of Auckland, so almost all of the electricity for Auckland and Northland must be transmitted from power stations in the south, mainly from Huntly Power Station and the Waikato River hydroelectric stations.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The city had two natural gas-fired power stations (the 404 MW Ōtāhuhu B and the 175 MW Southdown), but both shut down in 2015.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] There have been several notable power outages in Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The five-week-long 1998 Auckland power crisis blacked out much of the CBD after a cascade failure occurred on the four main underground cables supplying the CBD.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The 2006 Auckland Blackout interrupted supply to the CBD and many inner suburbs after an earth wire shackle at Transpower's Otāhuhu substation broke and short-circuited the lines supplying the inner city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] In 2009, much of the northern and western suburbs, as well as all of Northland, experienced a blackout when a forklift accidentally came into contact with the Ōtāhuhu to Henderson 220 kV line, the only major line supplying the region.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] These reduced the Auckland Region's reliance on Ōtāhuhu substation and northern and western Auckland's reliance on the Ōtāhuhu to Henderson line.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland was one of the original nine towns and cities in New Zealand to be supplied with natural gas when the Kapuni gas field entered production in 1970 and a 340 km long high-pressure pipeline from the field in Taranaki to the city was completed.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland was connected to the Maui gas field in 1982 following the completion of a high-pressure pipeline from the Maui gas pipeline near Huntly, via the city, to Whangārei in Northland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The high-pressure transmission pipelines supplying the city are now owned and operated by First Gas, with Vector owning and operating the medium and low-pressure distribution pipelines in the city.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Rugby union, cricket, rugby league, association football (soccer) and netball are widely played and followed.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] There are three racecourses within the city (Ellerslie and Avondale for thoroughbred racing, and Alexandra Park for harness racing).
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] A fourth racecourse is located at Pukekohe, straddling the boundary between Auckland and the neighbouring Waikato region.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Greyhound racing is held at Manukau Stadium.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Major events previously held in Auckland include the 1950 British Empire Games and the Commonwealth Games in 1990, and a number of matches (including the semi-finals and the final) of the 1987 Rugby World Cup and 2011 Rugby World Cup.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland hosted the America's Cup and Louis Vuitton Cup in 2000, 2003, and 2021.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The 2007 World Netball Championships were held at the Trusts Stadium.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The ITU World Triathlon Series held a Grand Final event in the Auckland CBD from 2012 until 2015.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The NRL Auckland Nines was a rugby league nines preseason competition played at Eden Park from 2014 to 2017.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The 2017 World Masters Games were held at a number of venues around Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The Auckland Darts Masters was held annually at The Trusts Arena from 2015 to 2018.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The Auckland urban area has 340 primary schools, 80 secondary schools, and 29 composite (primary/secondary combined) schools as of February 2012, catering for roughly 250,000 students.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The majority are state schools, but 63 schools are state-integrated and 39 are private.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland has some of the largest universities in the country.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Five of New Zealand's eight universities and eight of its fifteen polytechnics have campuses in Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] The University of Auckland, Auckland University of Technology, Manukau Institute of Technology, and Unitec Institute of Technology are based in Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Of institutions based in other regions, the University of Otago, Victoria University of Wellington, Massey University and several polytechnics have satellite campuses in Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland is a major centre of overseas language education, with large numbers of foreign students (particularly East Asians) coming to the city for several months or years to learn English or study at universities – although numbers New Zealand-wide have dropped substantially since peaking in 2003.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] As of 2007, there are around 50 New Zealand Qualifications Authority (NZQA) certified schools and institutes teaching English in the Auckland area.
[src:bastion-point/auckland-p02] Auckland Council maintains relationships with the following cities and countries.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Māori originally named the eastern point of the area Kohimarama, meaning to collect the remnants / wood chips, and the western point was named Takaparawhau.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Felton Mathew named the promontory South Head.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Just off that point was Bastion Rock, which was levelled and is now the site of the Tamaki Yacht Club.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Bastion Point became the common English name for the site encompassing both points.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The nearby beach known as Waiparera in Māori became known as Kohimarama.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, call it Takaparawhau, which, along with Ōkahu Bay, form Whenua Rangatira, which is vested in Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei for the common use and benefit of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei and citizens of Auckland, and is managed by the Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei Reserves Board.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The public land containing the Michael Joseph Savage Memorial and Fort Britomart tunnels is not owned by the hapū, who refer to it as Kohimarama, while Auckland Council now call it Takaparawhau.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The land was occupied by Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and before the colonisation of New Zealand it was part of important lands for the hapū, overlooking rich fishing and farming areas.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The surrounding land was purchased and confiscated by the New Zealand Government for public works and development over a period stretching from the 1840s into the 1950s.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] On 20 March 1840, in the Manukau Harbour area where Ngāti Whātua farmed, paramount chief Apihai Te Kawau signed the Treaty of Waitangi.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Soon after signing the treaty, Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, the primary hapū and landowner on the Auckland isthmus, made a strategic gift of 3,500 acres (1,400 hectares) of land on the Waitematā Harbour to William Hobson, the new Governor of New Zealand, for the new capital.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] By 1859, Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, who sold a further 13,200 acres (5,342 hectares) to the Crown, had lost most of their remaining land through speculators.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The 700-acre Ōrākei block was all that remained.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Within a century, this too was compulsorily acquired by the Crown (apart from a cemetery).
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Apihai Te Kawau spoke publicly against land sales and in order to safeguard a small amount of land in Ōrākei for future generations, and Te Kawau obtained a Crown Grant in 1869.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1873, the Native Land Court stated that "the land shall be inalienable".
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] A reversal of this government position came with the Validation Of Invalid Land Sales Act 1894.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1885, the New Zealand Government built a military outpost at Bastion Point, because of its commanding strategic position overlooking the Waitematā Harbour, known as Fort Bastion.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The outpost was not built on Takaparawha Point, which had earlier been taken by the Government for the same purpose.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1886, the Crown used the Public Works Act 1882 (46 Vict No 37) to take ownership of 13 acres (5.3 ha) of Bastion Point for this purpose of defence.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] From 1913 and 1928, the government bought most of the land that had been previously deemed inalienable.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1936, Ōrākei was proposed as a site for state housing by the First Labour Government, and in August a Māori delegation asked Prime Minister Savage that at least the marae on the flat foreshore where he had been ceremonially welcomed after his election should be retained by the tribe.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Savage was 'somewhat fogged' by the situation and asked for reports, which were not completed when he sailed to Britain for the Coronation and Imperial Conference in 1937.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Lee and Frank Langstone decided that the 120 Māori living at Ōrākei were illegal squatters and had to be removed.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The incensed Ōrākei Māori met Savage on his return from overseas, and he immediately reversed the decision, avoiding what could have been a political crisis.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Lee obtained most of his land, but Langstone's (and the Cabinet's) decision; seen as obtaining Māori land as a park 'for white children' was reversed.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Another motive for their proposal was to weaken Bill Endean's grip on Parnell, the only non-Labour seat in Auckland.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Māori from the pā met Savages' body when it arrived back in Auckland in 1940.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1941, the Crown no longer needed Bastion Point for defence, it did not return the land to its traditional Māori owners but instead gifted it to the Auckland City Council for a reserve.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] During World War II, three searchlights were housed in emplacements built at the foot of Bastion Point, and still exist today.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Guns, searchlights, and an anti-submarine boom stretched to Torpedo Bay near North Head, were installed at the front of the Tamaki Yacht Club, and were later incorporated into the yacht club building.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1951, Māori living in Ōrākei were evicted and the houses were knocked down.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] A justification for this eviction was health and sanitation issues, for which the government was ultimately responsible.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] These issues were created by the city council earlier when a sewer line and road were built along the foreshore which blocked the flow of storm water, creating the quagmire of sanitation problems.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] At the same time the village at Ōkahu Bay was not connected to the city's fresh water supply.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The first Labour Prime Minister of New Zealand, Michael Joseph Savage died in office in 1940, and is buried in an Art Deco mausoleum at Bastion Point designed by Tibor Donner and Anthony Bartlett with a sculpture by R.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Gross, built above the disused Fort Britomart.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] It has large columns, sunken gardens and a reflecting pool which was built in two years by Fletcher Construction for £34,533, with the cost raised by subscription.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The monument was dedicated before a crowd of ten thousand on 28 March 1943, with Savage's remains reinterred in a deep tunnel below the monument.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1976, the Crown announced that it planned to develop Bastion Point by selling it to the highest bidder for high-income housing.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Joe Hawke, members of his hapū Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and other activists, formed the Orakei Māori Action Committee, taking direct action to stop the subdivision.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The government claimed that the land had been sold to the Crown, however Hawke claimed that, "This land was not sold – it was confiscated under the Public Works Lands Act".
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] From 1977 to 1978, the Orakei Māori Action Committee organised and maintained an occupation of the remaining Crown land.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The occupation began on 5 January 1977, two days before construction of the housing was to start, to prevent its confiscation by the Muldoon Government.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The occupiers constructed a marae and housing, and grew crops.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] A fire in a tent on 26 September 1977 caused the death of a young girl named Joanna Hawke, the niece of protest leader Joe Hawke.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The occupation lasted for 506 days; it ended on 25 May 1978, when 800 police and personnel of the New Zealand Army forcibly removed the occupiers and destroyed the temporary buildings—including vegetable gardens and the marae.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Two hundred and twenty two protesters were arrested.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The occupation and the use of force to end it played a part in highlighting injustices against Māori, and the occupation became a major landmark in the history of Māori protest.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] In 1988, the New Zealand Labour Government returned Bastion Point and Ōrākei Marae to Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, with compensation, as part of a Treaty of Waitangi settlement process.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] The 1991 Ōrākei Act was passed to recognise the rights of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei under the treaty.
[src:bastion-point/bastion-point] Joe Hawke died on 22 May 2022, aged 82 and was buried at Bastion Point.
